```

Explanation:

1. The "name" property indicates the top-level node of the directory tree.
2. The "id" property is a unique identifier for each node within the directory tree.
3. Each "children" array contains a "name" property for each child node.
4. Each "children" array has an "id" property as well.
5. The "name" property and "id" properties for the "root" node are omitted.
6. The "children" array for the "root" node has one "name" property (i.e., "root"), and one "id" property.
7. The "children" array for each "folder1" node has two "name" properties (i.e., "folder1" and "id").
8. The "children" array for each "folder2" node has three "name" properties (i.e., "folder2", "id", and "id").
9. The "children" array for each "folder3" node has one "name" property (i.e., "folder3").
10. The "children" array for each "file1.txt" node has three "name" properties (i.e., "file1.txt", "id", and "id").
11. The "children" array for each "folder2" node has two "name" properties (i.e., "folder2", "id").
12. The "children" array for each "folder3" node has three "name" properties (i.e., "folder3", "id", and "id").
13. The "children" array for each "file3.txt" node has three "name" properties (i.e., "file3.txt", "id", and "id").
14. The "children" array for each "root" node has one "name" property (i.e., "root"), and one "id" property.

